Testing 1, 2, 3.
This is an interview with Mr. Delaney.
L.P. Delaney.
For a little over 30 years.
When did you first arrive in College Station?
I came to College Station on February the 14th, 1946.
And you've been here ever since?
Yes, I worked for the city.
until July the 1st, 1975.
Mr. Delaney, can you tell us a little bit about your family origins?
Where is your family from?
Where are you originally from?
Well, I came from Bonham, Texas.
I was born and reared in Bonham, in Fannin County.
It's up on the Red River, 90 miles northeast of Dallas.
And your parents, have they been there?
Well, my grandfather came to Texas when he was two years old with his family from Illinois.
Actually, the Delaneys came over from Ireland.
I don't know when, but they came from New York and drifted down to Virginia.
And my clan came across through Illinois to Texas.
Most of the Delaney's in Texas originated from these two brothers that came to Texas then.
I have a cousin that runs the Sam Raven Memorial up in Bonner, Sam Raven Library.
And he got all this.
Family tree.
Family tree and such stuff.
Well, that's pretty interesting.
What was your first job?
The college station for the city?
Well, I guess it was utility, Superintendent.
I was in charge, or you might call it director of public works then, because I looked after the maintenance of the streets and lights, water, sewer, and everything.
It was a very small town, I think 1,900 people.
And we had about 450 customers at that time.
Well, I imagine now they have 7,000 or 8,000 customers.
So it's grown.
What is your impression of the way that the city was run then and the way that they run it now?
What changes have you seen take place?
Well, the city at that time
you might say, a poor city.
They incorporated in 1938.
And I came here in 46.
So what does that make you?
Eight years old when I came here.
And we had our offices above the south side maintenance pharmacy over the south side, upstairs.
And our warehouse was an old Quonset hut building that sat up here where the 707
Texas Avenue or something.
So, I don't know, we just had one old army truck and a pickup.
And we did our work out of this.
We dug ditches for water lines by hand and light poles by hand and so forth until we kind of grew it and grew it.
And the city was able to buy better equipment.
You said that you attended A&M in what years?
I came to A&M in the fall of 1929.
I was in school only one year.
What was the campus like then?
What are some things you remember about it?
Well, in 29 and 30,
The highway was over where they call it the old highway now or old college road.
It came up College Avenue and turned into Triangle.
And all of this over in College Hills area, the new highway just wasn't here.
Even on the south side of the campus, there was a barbed wire fence along Jersey Street.
And this was a cornfield in there at that time.
This was the first year that Kyle Field was built.
They opened up Kyle Field in 29.
And they did away, the Tunerville Trolley quit running in 28.
The tracks were still laying off when I discovered it.
Well, do you think that...
Were they as spirited as they are now?
Oh, I would think more so.
Of course, everything that came in at that time came on the train almost.
The highways were all gravel.
I'd say from Bonham down here, it's about 300 miles.
There wasn't 100 miles of asphalt roads in 1929.
It was gravel that got off the main highway and dirt.
Well, even up to after I came here up to 1950, we had about eight passing trains a day that came through College Station.
Do you remember any... You've been here around City Hall or working for the city.
Has there ever been any interesting elections or political battles or anything of that sort?
I think most of the interesting elections have been in the last ten years.
15 years before that.
Well, it's just kind of old settlers around.
And like our first mayor, not our first mayor either, but Mr. Langford, who was the head of the architectural department, was mayor when I came here.
And he was mayor for over 20 years.
Well, just wouldn't anybody run against him.
And he did it as a service to the town.
And I'm sure they're still doing that, but some of them possibly have a little chip on their shoulder or want to change something.
Maybe it's the reason they're running.
You have more running today.
And of course, the town's larger, too.
Well, when the city was first established in 1938, was it like it is now, I mean, in such a close connection with Bryan, or was it sort of a separate little entity by itself, would you think?
Well, at that time, we purchased part of our water from Bryan and part from College, and we purchased all of our electricity from Bryan.
Now, the College Hills area
area east of Texas Avenue, Bryan, that was even an REA system that serviced all the houses.
And the city bought, purchased this REA system from Bryan in 1952, I believe it was.
And they had an agreement then with Bryan that any time the city took in land or
any area came into the city, well, Brian would sell the REA system then to Dollar Station.
And all the relations with Brian, all the time I was here, have been just first class, real good relations.
I think this energy situation has caused a lot of the write-ups in the papers now and a little friction.
But I don't think it'll ever be one city.
But I'll say it's one big community now.
I think the relations will stay there.
OK. Well, what do you do now for the city?
Are you sort of more or less just a?
No, I'm retired.
I don't do anything for the city unless they ask me to.
I did come back and work five weeks at first for this year when Mr. Ford had a light heart attack.
They asked me to come back.
So you're more or less kind of on call.
Well, I like that.
That's very nice.
You were here in 1946.
That was post-World War II, I was going to ask you.
That was right after the war.
So do you know, like, well, since A&M is a military school, would you have any idea?
Were the troops, do you know if troops were stationed here?
Or how the community would, well, I guess since it was post-World War II.
Well, right after the war, the city,

grew pretty real fast for a while because of all the boys coming back to finish their education and had to leave school and go and then to the government help them we had trailer homes all over the campus over there in fact they let them do that and this is when they built a college
College View, as it's called, and Hensel, and all.
They started building for the students at that time.
Before that, of course, it was just the boys.
Well, I'll say up until after the war, there were very few married students that came to A&M.
But after that, it kind of got to where
They were a little older when they came to school, and they were married.
So I guess it kind of changed the complexion of the university a little bit.
Do you remember any, I don't want to say disasters, but things like floods or tornadoes that maybe affected the community or affected the public work system that you had to deal with?
We have had several large rains on this little wolf pantry that goes in back of the Redmond Shopping Center that's caused some damage to apartments that were built below down there.
They just built it too low, in my opinion.
Of course, too, they had a lot of pavement put in, like when those apartments were built, I don't believe Texas Avenue, the curb and gutter was along by the campus.
Rain falls on pavement, it's not going in the ground, and it's just that much more for the preach to carry on, and it comes down past it.
This is the reason we had this problem.
We did in 1950, the winter of 49 and 50, we had an ice dam, what we call an ice dam that drizzly rains froze and
weighted the electric lines down, and I guess we had 40 or 50 light poles that were on the ground.
We had to work all night, but about two or three days later, we got cars back in.
The REA, they had some places out in the country off for two or three weeks.
So many light poles.
College, it took them about a week to get theirs all back.
It ran all the way down.
That was quite a bit of work.
You know, when I came to school in 1929, that winter, we had six inches of snow on the campus.
There was 24 inches at Waco.
If we had to go to Bonham, you had to go to Waco and back up to Dallas.
There wasn't any cutting across on the 29th.
Goodness.
We'd go home six days in that snow.
Oh, dear.
Oh, does your family, like, do you have children?
Yes, I had two children, a boy and a girl.
And they were brought up here?
Yes.
We felt like when we moved to College Station that this was the perfect place to have your children.
And, well, of course, we both liked that place before we ever came, and...
Shortly after we were here, we just took them one night and decided this was our home.
We were going to stay here and make this our home.
They were, one was three years old and one four and a half, I believe, when we moved here.
Where's your wife from?
She's from Fort Outon.
She was born and raised in Fort Outon.
She taught school.
in the second grade for 30 years in college.
Oh, really?
But she's retired now also?
Yes, she's retired.
Well, I'll tell you, and this is no joke, but you don't look old enough to be retired to me.
I don't know how old you are, but my cousin was telling me that your wife was, I think she said your wife was her teacher.
And she was a real nice lady and a real good teacher, and she's been teaching for a long time.
So y'all have been a pretty...
important part of the community in one way or the other, it seems like.
Well, we think the community was real good to us.
We hope we helped some, but really it's been a pleasure living here all this time.
Well, I think that's about all, unless you have something else you'd like to tell me.
I'll be interested in anything that you'd like to talk about or say.
I notice your middle name is Pierce.
Where did this come from?
Well, you might say back in the olden days, most people named their children after their mother's parents or their father's parents.
And the Pierce, my grandmother on my father's side, was a Pierce.
They lived in Fannin County, too, of course.
This is where I got my middle name.
I have an older brother whose middle name is Seals.
And that's our grandmother.
My mother's name was Seals before she died.
And the Louis, does that have any origins?
Yes.
My older sister was studying.
about Louis XIV, so my mother said when I was born, and she wanted to name me after Louis XIV.
Okay, well.
Mr. Delaney, you were telling me about a little story about Richard Carter and the cemetery.
Could you repeat that just a little bit again for me, please?
Well, Richard Carter's home was...
out near the east bypass.
And just northeast of his home, they had a little cemetery, a family private cemetery, as most of the old settlers had.
I believe the last burial in that cemetery, which had about nine small tombstones, was in 1875.
The reason I'm
found this cemetery and knew about it, Mr. Langford wanted me to go with him one day in the late 40s to help locate it and look at it as a possible site for a cemetery for the City College Station.
Mr. Langford was the mayor?
Mr. Langford was the mayor of College Station at that time.
By the way, they didn't use this location.
They used the Methodist Cemetery out on Texas Avenue
about a mile toward Houston on the right.
But this was a little cemetery.
It had a steel picket fence around it about four feet high, and it was about 25 feet square, a little gate.
Well, when they built the East Bypass, the state highway men who were
trying to locate it, came by the city hall and asked me if I would go out and show them where the Richard Carter Cemetery was so they'd be sure and miss it with the east bypass.
We went out there and searched and searched, and finally I found where the cemetery was.
It's just the cemetery disappeared.
I take it someone stole the fence and took the stones for stepping stones or something.
I don't know.
And I came in and reported it to our chief of police and called the Texas Ranger and told him somebody had stolen Richard Carter's cemetery.
This sounds kind of crazy, but that's exactly what happened.
I haven't heard any more about it since.
You also mentioned something about...

an epidemic that broke out in the When the railroad tracks ended at Milliken and Milliken was a town of about 30,000 According to their old stories Sanger Harris was at Milliken until they tied the railroad tracks together to Dallas and then they moved to Dallas Well

My wife's grandfather said that they left Milliken when he was nine years old because it was they had a yellow fever epidemic there and people just left and shortly after that well of course they continued the railroad on to Dallas and Milliken just is about
I would say 200 people now.
Just never has grown back to its original size.
That's right.
My wife's folks moved to Reagan, Texas.
I see.
I guess that's the last of that story.
I guess so.
Thank you.
